The '''Royal Grammar School''' is an English [[Independent school|independent]] day school for boys in [[Guildford]], [[Surrey]]. It was founded in 1509 by the will of Robert Beckingham, a wealthy grocer, and moved to the present site on the [[High Street]] after the granting of a royal charter from [[Edward VI of England|King Edward VI]] in 1552. The school is home to a rare example of a [[chained library]] established by [[John Parkhurst]], Bishop of Norwich, in 1575 and is also the site of the first recorded game of cricket around the year 1550.[[#cricket|<sup>[a]</sup>]] The current headmaster is Dr. Jon Cox who has occupied the post since 2007 and is the 35th headmaster of the school. The school is a member of the [[Headmasters' and Headmistresses' Conference]] and has a reputation for being one of the top schools academically in the country.

Tuition at the school was initially free, but with the introduction of comprehensive education and the abolition of grammar schools the school became independent and fee paying in 1977 . The school now has approximately 900 students, about 300 of whom are in the sixth form. However the school maintains a grammar school ethos, and as such operates numerous outreach schemes for local students in maintained education.

==History==
The founding of the [[school]] dates to 1509 and the death of Robert Beckingham, a wealthy [[grocer]], and a member of the [[Worshipful Company of Grocers]] and a [[Freeman of the City of London]]. In his will he requested that the parishioners of St Olave's church, [[Southwark]], should obtain a licence to endow a chantry priest to say masses for his soul. If they failed to do this within two years of his death, his executors had discretion either to use the property to 'make a free scole at the Towne of Guldford' or to put the income to some other good charitable use.<ref name="surhist">{{cite news |url=http://www.exploringsurreyspast.org.uk/GetRecord/SHCOL_1775_(PART2OF2) |title=ROYAL GRAMMAR SCHOOL (FORMERLY THE FREE GRAMMAR SCHOOL OF KING EDWARD VI), GUILDFORD: RECORDS, 1553-1965 |last= |first= |date= |work=Surrey History: Exploring Surrey's Past |accessdate=20 December 2010 |location=}}</ref> The license was not obtained within the required time, and so in 1512, Beckingham's executors formerly conveyed the lands in the bequest to a body of trustees consisting of the Mayor of Guildford and four 'sad and discrete men' who had formerly been mayors. With the rents they were to provide a free grammar school in Guildford with a 'sufficient schoolmaster',<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.rgs-guildford.co.uk/page_viewer.asp?page=Brief+History+of++the+School&pid=12 |title=Royal Grammar School Website |accessdate=2010-012-20}}</ref>  to teach thirty "of the poorest-men's sons" to read and write English and cast accounts perfectly, so that they would be fit to become apprentices.<ref>Brayley, p370</ref>

[[Image:RGS old building.jpg|250px|left|thumb|''The Old Building'']]

Over the coming years the school ran into considerable finical difficulty and so The Mayor and Approved Men of Guildford petitioned [[Edward VI of England|Edward VI]] to grant them further endowments for maintenance. One of the kings closest advisors, [[William Parr, 1st Marquess of Northampton|William Parr]], had a particular affection for the town having himself spent a large amount of time as the Kings manor house in Guildford, and it was he who advised the King to re-appropriate some of the funds arising from the [[Chantries Acts#Abolition of Chantries Acts.2C 1545 and 1547|Abolition of the Chantries Acts]] to the school.<ref>Russel, p.97</ref> Thus in January 1552 Edward VI ordered that there was to be "one Grammar School in Guildford called the Free Grammar School of King Edward VI for the education, institution and instruction of boys and youths in Grammar at all future times forever to endure", along with a grant of 20 pounds per year. The high street site was purchased in 1555 with the construction of the [[Listed building|Grade I listed]] [[Tudor style architecture|Tudor]] Old Building<ref name="engherlist">{{cite web | url=http://www.heritagegateway.org.uk/Gateway/Results_Single.aspx?uid=288983&resourceID=5 |title=Heritage Gateway |accessdate=26 December 2010}}</ref> starting in 1557. It was finally completed in 1586.

The death of Dr.[[John Parkhurst]], the [[Bishop of Norwich]], in 1575 resulted in the founding of the schools' chained library.<ref>Brayley, p70</ref> In his will he gave "the most parte of all my Latten bookes whereof shall be made a catalogue as shortelie as I may God sendinge me lief." although obtaining these books was not without its difficulties. Since this date the library has been added to, most notably between 1600 and 1800.<ref>Cambray, p554</ref> The library is housed within the Gallery (now the Headmaster's Study) in the Old Building, with the present bookcases dating from 1897. The oldest book within the library was printed in [[Venice]] around the year 1480, with the oldest english book printed in circa 1500 bearing the imprint of [[Wynkyn de Worde]]. Today the library is one of the few remaining examples of a chained library located within a school.<ref name="chain">{{cite web |url=http://www.rgs-guildford.co.uk/page_viewer.asp?page=+The+Chained+Library&pid=13 |title=School Website - Chained Library |accessdate=4 February 2011}}</ref>

{{anchor|cricket}}In 1598, a court case about an ownership dispute over a plot of land located somewhere along the lower high street referred to a sport called ''kreckett'' being played at the school around 1550. John Derrick, one of the queens coroners for the county of Surrey attested that some 50 years earlier ''"When he was a scholler in the free school of Guldeford, he and several of his fellowes did runne and play there at kreckett and other plaies."''<ref>Russel, p.203</ref> The [[Oxford English Dictionary]] gives this as the first recorded instance of [[cricket]] in the [[English language]].<ref name="cc1">{{cite web | url=http://oed.com/viewdictionaryentry/Entry/44388 |title=Oxford English Dictionary Online |accessdate=2009-09-30}}</ref><ref name="cc7">{{cite web | url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/story/239757.html  |title=ESPN CricInfo - History  |accessdate=26 December 2010}}</ref>

[[File:Royal_Grammar_School,_Guildford_-_Original_Charter.jpg|250px|right|thumb|''The original charter granted to the school by [[Edward VI of England|King Edward VI]]'']]

After the granting of the charter, it took 50 years before the first set of statutes to govern the school were completed. They were finally approved by the [[Bishop of Winchester]] on 16 September 1608, and they constituted a major change in the way the school was run. Up until this point the boys were instructed in English and accounting, but following the statutes lessons were in the subjects of [[Latin language|Latin]] and [[Ancient Greek|Greek]], with students required to speak in Latin unless licensed by the master to do otherwise. Admissions following the charter changed, with  "''none to be admitted scholar into the said school before he be brought to the schoolmaster of that school, and upon his examination shall be found to have learned the rudiments of grammar, called the Accidence."'' All scholars from Guildford were required to pay the master 5 [[shillings]] on admission to the school, or if he was not from the town the charge was 10s. The number of pupils at the school was capped at 100, although this number was rarely reached. The statues also saw the introduction of school fees. Although the defined as a "free" school fees were still charged at the rate of 4s per annum, paid as 9d per quarter, with an additional shilling due on the feast of [[St. Michael]], which was used to pay for "clean, wax candles".<ref>Brayley, p371</ref>

In 1866 the then headmaster Revd Henry G Merriman (Headmaster 1859-75) purchased Allen House, a large house set in extensive grounds which stood opposite the school. The house took its name from Anthony Allen, Master of Chancery and Mayor of Guildford in 1740. This was initially used as a boarding house for the school between 1866-74 before later being purchased by [[Surrey County Council]] in 1921 and was used by the school up until its demolition in 1964. The grounds surrounding the house were purchased in 1914 by HA Powell and donated to the school as playing fields.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.rgs-guildford.co.uk/page_viewer.asp?page=Buildings&pid=16 |title=Royal Grammar School Website |accessdate=2010-12-20}}</ref> 

During the mid to late 19th century the school fell into disrepair and decay. Guildford Municipal Charities established a committee to report into the general condition of the school and the buildings. The committee reported in 1881 that the school had no funds available for repairs and that there were only 9 boys 'instead of the former ordinary number of 100'. Various suggestions were made by the Charity Commission to raise funds for the school, including a reorganisation with [[George Abbot School|Archbishop Abbot's School]],  The Committee for Maintaining Higher Education in Guildford was established in Mar 1887 to oppose the Charity Commission's draft scheme to amalgamate the RGS, Nettle's Charity and Archbishop Abbot's School. The committee raised <U+00A3>2,238.15s.4d (approximately <U+00A3>108,000 in 2010)<ref>http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/currency/results.asp#mid</ref> towards the restoration of the RGS, ensuring its survival.<ref name="surhist"/> A new Charity Commission scheme came into effect in November 1888  which resulted in the Old Building being restored, and the schools continuation as a day only school. Several years later under the [[Education Act 1944]] the school adopted [[voluntary controlled school|voluntary controlled]] status; tuition was therefore free and entrance was to be by common examination at the age of eleven.

The construction of the New Building started in 1958 in the grounds of Allen House and initially consisted of a gymnasium, assembly hall, dining hall and kitchens, caretaker's flat, staff common rooms, junior library, cloakrooms and changing rooms, eight classrooms, science lecture theatre, five science laboratories, geography and art rooms, and various offices, stores and smaller rooms arranged in a J shape. The construction of the initial building was finished in 1963.

[[Image:RGS Guildford 500 Logo.png|thumb|alt=RGS Guildford 500 Logo|The Logo used by the school during the year 2009/2010, to celebrate the 500th anniversary of the founding of the school.]]

On the morning of Sunday 2 December a fire ripped through the Old Building, gutting a large part of the building including the two oldest rooms in the school, School Room and Big School. It is thought that the fire started in the Hamonde room ([[England|English]] master JC Mallison<U+2019>s classroom), although the actual cause of the fire is still unknown. The main priority of the numerous members of staff and friends of the school who tried to help was to save the books in the Chained Library from being damaged by flames, smoke or water from the Fire Brigade<U+2019>s hose pipes. The books were saved but one casualty of the rescue was [[Art]] master Ron Smoothey, who was injured by a water-filled lampshade falling on his head. Rebuilding took two and a half years, partly because the [[Winter of 1962<U+2013>1963 in the United Kingdom|Big Freeze]] of early 1963 meant that work could not proceed normally with temperatures dropping to -17C at night.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.rgs-guildford.co.uk/_files/newsletters/1848-Newsletter2.pdf |title=RGS Foundation Newsletter |accessdate=2010-12-20}}</ref> 

The School became independent in 1977 when the parents and staff of the school, lead by the Chairman of the Governors, John Fergrieve Brown, raised sufficient funds to purchase the school.  As a result the RGS withdrew from the [[government]] maintained system becoming independent and fee paying. This was followed the following year by the purchase of [[Lanesborough School|Lanesborough Preparatory School]] which became the junior school, preparing boys for entry to the RGS at either 11 or 13.

More recently in 2003 construction finished on a new <U+00A3>5 million Sports Centre and All Weather Training Area with Shooting Range. Followed shortly after in 2006 refurbishments were made to the Old Building site with the old gymnasium being converted into a Sixth Form Centre and the [[Victorian era|Victorian]] science laboratories (some of the earliest in the country) have been converted to the Art School.

In the year 2009/2010 the school celebrated the Quincentennial Anniversary of the founding of the school by Robert Beckingham, numerous events were organised, including the commissioning of a new musical work by the Director of Music, Peter White, entitled "Shall Life Inherit" based loosely on the school hymn [[To be a Pilgrim]] by [[John Bunyan]].<ref name="getsurrey1">{{cite news |url=http://www.getsurrey.co.uk/news/s/2067523_teacher_set_for_guildford_cathedral_music_premiere |title=Teacher set for Guildford Cathedral music prmiere |last=Millers |first=Vita |date=12 March 2010 |work=Get Surrey Online |accessdate=20 December 2010 |location=Guildford}}</ref> This year also saw a visit from [[HRH The Princess Royal]].<ref name="getsurrey2">{{cite news |url=http://www.getsurrey.co.uk/news/s/2071121_princess_visits_500yearold_royal_grammar_school |title=Princess visits 500-year-old Royal Grammar School |last= |first= |date=14 May 2010 |work=Get Surrey Online |accessdate=20 December 2010 |location=Guildford}}</ref><ref name="ndesk">{{cite news |url=http://www.mynewsdesk.com/uk/view/news/buckingham-palace-national-royal-diary-of-engagements-31st-march-2010-5007 |title=List of Royal Engagements |last= |first= |date= 31 March 2010 |work= |accessdate=22 December 2010 |location=}}</ref>

